What is the difference between Amazon RDS and Amazon Aurora?
Amazon RDS is a managed relational database service that supports multiple database engines, while Amazon Aurora is a
proprietary database engine developed by AWS that is compatible with MySQL and PostgreSQL. Aurora offers enhanced performance,
scalability, and availability compared to standard RDS instances.
============================================================================================================================
How do you perform a point-in-time recovery for an RDS instance?
To perform a point-in-time recovery for an RDS instance, navigate to the RDS console, select the desired database instance,
and click on 'Restore to point in time'. Choose the specific date and time you want to restore to, and then create a new RDS instance from that point.
============================================================================================================================
How can you automate the backup process for an RDS instance using AWS Lambda?
To automate the backup process for an RDS instance using AWS Lambda, you can create a Lambda function that triggers the backup
process by calling the create_db_snapshot method from the Boto3 library. Schedule this Lambda function using Amazon CloudWatch
Events to run at regular intervals, ensuring consistent and automated backups
============================================================================================================================
Explain the concept of database migration in RDS and the tools available for it?
Database migration in RDS involves transferring data from an existing database to an RDS instance. AWS provides several tools for this purpose,
including the AWS Database Migration Service (DMS) for continuous data replication, the AWS Schema Conversion Tool for converting database schemas,
and native database tools like mysqldump or pg_dump for one-time migrations.
